      <lg type="edition">
<l>alaṅkukatir cumanta kalaṅkaṟ cūḻi</l>
<l>nilaitaḷarvu tolainta volkunilaip palkāṟ</l>
<l>potiyi loruciṟai paḷḷi yāka</l>
<l>muḻāaraip pōntai yaravāy māmaṭa</l>
<l>ṉārum pōḻuṅ kiṇaiyoṭu curukki</l>
<l>yēriṉ vāḻnar kuṭimuṟai pukāa</l>
<l>vūḻiran tuṇṇu muyaval vāḻvaip</l>
<l>puravetirntu koḷḷuñ cāṉṟōr yāreṉap</l>
<l>piracan tūṅku maṟāa yāṇar</l>
<l>varaiyaṇi paṭappai naṉṉāṭṭup poruna</l>
<l>poyyā vīkaik kaḻaṟoṭi yāay</l>
<l>yāvaru miṉmaiyiṟ kiṇaippat tāvatu</l>
<l>perumaḻai kaṭaṟparan tāaṅ kiyāṉu</l>
<l>moruniṉ ṉuḷḷi vantaṉe ṉataṉāṟ</l>
<l>pulavar pukki lāki nilavarai</l>
<l>nilīiya rattai nīyē yoṉṟē</l>
<l>niṉṉiṉṟu vaṟuvi tākiya vulakattu</l>
<l>nilavaṉ mārō puravalar tuṉṉip</l>
<l>periya vōtiṉuñ ciṟiya vuṇarāp</l>
<l>pīṭiṉṟu perukiya tiruviṟ</l>
<l>pāṭiṉ maṉṉaraip pāṭaṉmā remarē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>[Our] living in suffering, when [we], (7cd)</l>
<l>by a pond with muddy water burdened with swaying ears, (1)</l>
<l>with in one wing of the public hall [our] resting place, (3)</l>
<l>with many many rafters in a weakened state, lost when bending over from [their] position, (2)</l>
<l>having folded with the Kiṇai drum leather straps and the fibre  </l>
<l>of the big fronds from a palmyra tree with drum[-like] trunk, (4f.)</l>
<l>enter one by one the homes of those who live by the plough, (6)</l>
<l>  beg in turns [and] eat, (7cd) </l>
<l>fails, so that it sounds: (12cd)</l>
<l>“who are the exemplary people who will meet [us] with protection?” (8)</l>
<l>  in the absence of anybody (12ab)</l>
<l>[like] Āay with anklets [and] bracelets, with gifts that are not false, (11) </l>
<l>o fighter of a good land with gardens near the mountains (10)</l>
<l>of unceasing fertility where honeycombs hang. (9) </l>
<l>Spreading like a sea of big clouds(?) I too (13)</l>
<l>have come, remembering only you. Therefore, (14)</l>
<l>may you stand a mountain on earth, the one [and only],</l>
<l>as a house to be entered by scholars! (15f.)</l>
<l>In a world that has become empty without you (17)</l>
<l>protectors won’t last. Although approaching [them], (18)</l>
<l>reciting a lot, perceiving little, (19)</l>
<l>our people won’t sing kings not favoured (21)</l>
<l>by Fortune who have become great without honour. (20)</l>
<l>15f.</l>
<l>may you stand on earth (what to do with oṉṟē?)	</l>
<l>18d-21</l>
<l>  Approaching [them]</l>
<l>our people won’t sing kings without song, </l>
<l>with fortune that has become big without honour,</l>
<l>who, although having recited (~ learned) much, understand little.   </l>
</lg>
